    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_4014470149" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4014470149" />
    <a title="Fadillah" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/16105107-fadillah"><img alt="Fadillah" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1594898999p2/16105107.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4014470149?book_show_action=true">May 21, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Fadillah" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Fadillah" href="/user/show/16105107-fadillah">Fadillah</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16105107-fadillah?shelf=asian-literature">asian-literature</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16105107-fadillah?shelf=memoir-autobiography">memoir-autobiography</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16105107-fadillah?shelf=women-writers">women-writers</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4014470149" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4305356390213615416">I knew that I was the least-loved child because I was a girl and because my mother had died giving birth to me.<br/>- Adeline Yen Mah , Falling Leaves: The Memoir of an Unwanted Chinese Daughter<br/>.<br/>.<br/>I read Chinese Cinderella first back in february before i dived deeply into this book. I know one was supposed to follow the sequence but life happens so bear with it. I think reading the second book first did help me in building the framework of Adeline Yen Mah’s life. I believe it provide me with the found</span>
  <span id="freeText4305356390213615416" style="display:none">I knew that I was the least-loved child because I was a girl and because my mother had died giving birth to me.<br />- Adeline Yen Mah , Falling Leaves: The Memoir of an Unwanted Chinese Daughter<br />.<br />.<br />I read Chinese Cinderella first back in february before i dived deeply into this book. I know one was supposed to follow the sequence but life happens so bear with it. I think reading the second book first did help me in building the framework of Adeline Yen Mah’s life. I believe it provide me with the foundation and by the time i finished the first book, i can see the whole structure. Weird analogy but thats how i felt while reading it. The first book brought so much details of what has been summarised in a second book. It brought the readers back to how the friendship of her mother with Aunt Baba was formed and eventually on to why Aunt Baba is always there for her, how her father business expanded with her Grandfather’s assistance, how her father meet with her step mother, Niang and ended up put her on the pedestal and ended up overlooking the other family. A lot of things happened to Adeline and one could never help but felt pity towards her. I have said this in my second book and i think i will reiterate again that i hate Niang and His father with every fiber of my being. I am glad that Adeline acknowledge her father’s male supremacy by recalling her childhood memories. Escaping from the prospective of arranged marriage and Niang Abusive manner altogether is what Adeline really wanted and she got it when she further her study in London. She rationalized that whatever she faced in London, it is much better than being the subject of Niang’s torment. Hence come the racism towards the Chinese, exoticization and fetishization of Asian girl and the subtle patronization of the so called liberal students in her daily life. Adeline just took things in stride and just focused on to graduate ASAP. I am a bit uncomfortable with Adeline’s relationship with her lecturer, Karl. For him to be twice her age and insisting for the relationship to be hidden as the time is not right, all i see is the red flag. I am glad Adeline ended the relationship when she went to Hong Kong. Unfortunately, Hong Kong turned into a nightmare for Adeline. Niang and her father decided to unleash their emotional blackmail on her. Her career did not thrive and she was constantly on her toes trying to please both of them. She escaped to USA and decided to build her career there. USA may have a promising premise for her but Adeline fell for Byron and married. She discovered right away that Byron was nothing but a fraud. She still couldnt leave Byron and intend to make the marriage work. ‘Shame’ of being a divorcee and trying to save face or what will people say ran deeply in her upbringing pushing her to endure every emotional and domestic abuse by Byron. Honestly, i was so frustrated by this turn of event. I understood why she what she did but God, sometimes Asian values can be so toxic that one will put society and family first before one’s mental and physical well being - (Before anyone attacked me, i am an Asian myself). Overall, this book is not to be read in one sitting or else you will lose your mind over the injustice and unfair treatment that Adeline faced as a ‘Fifth daughter’. Occassionally, you see that Karma returned throughout the book - whatever Franklin did to her being paid in his demise over eating a contaminated strawberry or Niang who loved Frankie so much paid a price of losing him and on the other hands, Lydia being miserable in her loveless marriage while watching her siblings living abroad and each successful in their career. I would recommend this if you are ready to venture into the story whereby the main story is truly a chinese cinderella, no matter how badly she was treated, she still see the goodness in people. </span>
  <a data-text-id="4305356390213615416" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


